# Task Management App тАФ Chapter 3: Microkernel Architecture

Part of a 5-chapter series building one Task Management Platform across 5 architecture patterns.

**Book:** Software Architecture Patterns тАФ Mark Richards
**Chapter:** 3 тАФ Microkernel Architecture
**Author:** Adedotun Adewole Stephen
**GitHub:** github.com/444notdotun

---

## What This Chapter Covers

Implementing the Microkernel (Plugin) Architecture pattern by building a notification system where delivery channels are plugins that plug into a stable core engine тАФ with no changes to the core when new channels are added.

The notification system also applies the **Strategy Pattern** under the hood тАФ each plugin is an interchangeable strategy for delivering a notification.

---

## Architecture

```
CORE SYSTEM
тФФтФАтФА NotificationManager
      тФФтФАтФА Map<String, NotificationPlugin>
            тФЬтФАтФА EMAIL_NOTIFICATION тЖТ GmailSender
            тФФтФАтФА SMS_NOTIFICATION   тЖТ SmsNotification

EVENT FLOW (EDA layer)
UserService
  тЖТ publishes UserRegisteredEvent
    тЖТ UserRegistrationConsumer (async)
      тЖТ builds NotificationRequest (type = EMAIL)
        тЖТ NotificationManager routes to GmailSender
          тЖТ email delivered via JavaMailSender

UserService
  тЖТ publishes PasswordChangedEvent
    тЖТ UserRegistrationConsumer (async)
      тЖТ builds NotificationRequest (type = SMS)
        тЖТ NotificationManager routes to SmsNotification
          тЖТ SMS delivered via Termii API

AUDIT
Every notification тЖТ AuditLog saved to PostgreSQL
```

---

## Tech Stack

- Java 17
- Spring Boot 3
- Spring Events (ApplicationEventPublisher)
- Spring Data JPA
- PostgreSQL
- JavaMailSender (Gmail SMTP)
- Termii SMS API
- Maven

---

## Patterns Applied

| Pattern | Where |
|---------|-------|
| Microkernel | NotificationManager + plugin registry |
| Strategy | NotificationPlugin interface + interchangeable implementations |
| EDA | Spring Events for async decoupled communication |
| Dependency Injection | Spring wires all plugins into Map at startup |
| Audit Log | Every notification event recorded to PostgreSQL |

---

## How Plugins Are Registered

Spring automatically injects all `NotificationPlugin` implementations into a `Map<String, NotificationPlugin>` using the `@Component` bean name as the key.

```java
// Plugin registration тАФ zero manual wiring needed
@Component("EMAIL_NOTIFICATION")
public class GmailSender implements NotificationPlugin { ... }

@Component("SMS_NOTIFICATION")
public class SmsNotification implements NotificationPlugin { ... }

// Core system тАФ Spring injects the map automatically
public NotificationManager(Map<String, NotificationPlugin> notificationPluginMap) {
    this.notificationPluginMap = notificationPluginMap;
}
```

To add a new channel тАФ write a new class, annotate it with `@Component("PUSH_NOTIFICATION")`. Zero changes to `NotificationManager`.

